        <section data-uuid="e5d0a2c6b2b546289acbcd492e80e61b" class="segment-opener">
            <article data-uuid="3575c6d5f9534f84821769122dbffe69">
                <h4 data-uuid="859d72055a75476f886eac3f4c30d34a">Main Idea</h4>
                <p data-uuid="97bdce4a28fa4672a1046465947159c1" class="main-idea">The
                    Empire of Ghana was the first of three great West African trading kingdoms.</p>
                <h2 data-uuid="f84c42d3bb7143e998d7c8ad123ff7d9">Empire
                    of Ghana</h2>
                <div data-uuid="54a6a23867d24e7691ca1573c546d4f4" class="yellow-star-yellow-bar"></div>
            </article>
        </section>
        <section data-uuid="6176c63c4d5a44549887debcda38576f" class="graphic-organizer-prompt ">
            <div data-uuid="de36ee2b2132458fa85f50832f8cc2df" class="go-prompt-bottom-bar">
                <p data-uuid="0914b213bbd24870afc88323982771db">As
                    you read, use the graphic organizer to take notes on the trading kingdoms of West Africa.</p>
            </div>
        </section>
        <p data-uuid="6d40a9332e864f9cbf4e72af30a27ab4">By
            1500 West Africa was well known for its trading kingdoms. Since ancient times,
            despite the dangers of the Sahara, trade routes crisscrossed West Africa. For
            many years, <b><dfn title="Berbers">Berbers</dfn></b>, a group
            of people from northern Africa, controlled these routes. In time, however, a
            series of three great trading empires arose thanks to the control of the salt
            and gold trades. Ghana (GAH-nuh) was the first of these empires.</p>
